407
00:24:52.124 --> 00:24:56.074
So natural killer cells are part of our innate immune system, are particularly

408
00:24:56.084 --> 00:24:59.894
attractive for allogeneic cell therapy because in the allogeneic setting,

409
00:25:00.394 --> 00:25:02.474
they don't cause graft versus host disease.

410
00:25:03.034 --> 00:25:04.894
Killing is mediated through multiple

411
00:25:05.754 --> 00:25:09.054
innate receptors, endogenous receptors through which NK cells can

412
00:25:09.114 --> 00:25:09.834
recognize

413
00:25:10.654 --> 00:25:14.454
abnormal cells, such as cancer cells, and of course, you add your CAR,

414
00:25:14.494 --> 00:25:16.394
now you have multiple mechanisms of killing.

415
00:25:16.954 --> 00:25:20.194
And NK cells are also a mediator of antibody-dependent cellular

416
00:25:20.234 --> 00:25:23.974
cytotoxicity through the CD16 receptor, and the reason

417
00:25:24.034 --> 00:25:27.414
why many monoclonal antibodies we use in the clinic actually work.

418
00:25:28.614 --> 00:25:32.564
They have a very attractive safety profile in that cases of

419
00:25:32.594 --> 00:25:35.884
CRS and ICANS are not as common after CAR NK

420
00:25:36.234 --> 00:25:36.634
cells.

421
00:25:37.674 --> 00:25:39.974
Although there are certainly some questions around

422
00:25:41.114 --> 00:25:43.934
NK cell therapies in that they have a limited lifespan.

423
00:25:45.174 --> 00:25:48.914
NK cells, in the absence of cytokine support, only have a one to

424
00:25:48.954 --> 00:25:52.874
two-week lifespan, and it's still unclear what's the best starting population

425
00:25:52.914 --> 00:25:56.454
for manufacturing. And that's why multiple different groups are looking at

426
00:25:56.494 --> 00:26:00.394
different strategies, including peripheral blood, obviously, NK cell

427
00:26:00.434 --> 00:26:02.534
lines, induced pluripotent stem cells.

428
00:26:02.574 --> 00:26:06.254
We work with cord blood, partly because at MD Anderson, we have our own

429
00:26:06.334 --> 00:26:10.234
cord blood bank, which was established by my colleague and good friend, Dr.

430
00:26:10.254 --> 00:26:13.754
Spall. And we've developed the

431
00:26:13.994 --> 00:26:15.274
SOPs to generate

432
00:26:16.434 --> 00:26:20.274
50 to 100-plus doses of CAR NK cells from one cord

433
00:26:20.354 --> 00:26:24.234
blood unit in a two-week manufacturing process at a cost of only

434
00:26:24.314 --> 00:26:28.134
a few hundred dollars or a couple of thousand dollars to us, which we

435
00:26:28.174 --> 00:26:30.674
can then biobank and use to

436
00:26:32.334 --> 00:26:35.574
support multiple different trials, asking different questions.

437
00:26:36.334 --> 00:26:38.514
So a few years ago now, we started a

438
00:26:40.914 --> 00:26:44.694
phase one first-in-human trial where we took cord blood NK

439
00:26:44.734 --> 00:26:48.394
cells, then we engineered them with this viral vector that was shared with us by

440
00:26:48.494 --> 00:26:51.274
Pietro Dotti when he was at Baylor College of Medicine.

441
00:26:51.774 --> 00:26:54.794
And this was an interleukin-15 armored CAR,

442
00:26:55.854 --> 00:26:59.814
IL-15 supporting the proliferation of the NK cells, and it also incorporated

443
00:26:59.894 --> 00:27:03.834
a safety switch. So we published the data on the phase

444
00:27:03.934 --> 00:27:04.914
one and phase two

445
00:27:06.734 --> 00:27:08.554
elements of this trial,

446
00:27:09.434 --> 00:27:13.394
and we show a very excellent safety profile, very promising

447
00:27:13.404 --> 00:27:17.034
activity, but also something that was very interesting to us, an

448
00:27:17.074 --> 00:27:20.934
observation that we made was that the quality of the umbilical

449
00:27:21.054 --> 00:27:25.014
cord blood unit that we had used for manufacturing of our CAR NK

450
00:27:25.094 --> 00:27:28.514
cells was a very important determinant of response.

451
00:27:28.554 --> 00:27:32.274
In that if we use CAR NK cells from cord blood units that were frozen

452
00:27:32.314 --> 00:27:35.754
within 24 hours of collection and with a nucleated red blood count

453
00:27:35.774 --> 00:27:39.754
of 80 million, our one-year progression free survival was actually

454
00:27:40.034 --> 00:27:43.294
70% with a one-year overall survival of 95%.

455
00:27:44.594 --> 00:27:48.094
Patients who received CAR NK cells from cord blood units frozen

456
00:27:49.214 --> 00:27:53.053
after 24 hours of collection and with a higher nucleated red blood

457
00:27:53.134 --> 00:27:55.154
count, as you can see, had a dismal outcome.

458
00:27:55.734 --> 00:27:57.814
And then we validated this in

459
00:27:59.254 --> 00:28:03.054
multiple mouse models. We looked at the transcriptomic profile and

460
00:28:03.114 --> 00:28:05.614
epigenomic profile, and we really demonstrated that

461
00:28:05.654 --> 00:28:09.334
this starting population was very important.

462
00:28:09.874 --> 00:28:13.794
And so since then, we've also done a lot of studies comparing NK

463
00:28:13.994 --> 00:28:17.754
cells from different sources. Specifically, and this is a collaboration with

464
00:28:17.834 --> 00:28:21.494
Ken Chan and work that is being led by Vaku Mohenji and Merve Dede,

465
00:28:22.214 --> 00:28:25.994
where we looked at NK cells that were isolated from cord blood

466
00:28:26.494 --> 00:28:29.294
versus those from peripheral blood and versus

467
00:28:29.694 --> 00:28:32.394
developmental NK from a published

468
00:28:33.214 --> 00:28:36.354
single-cell data from fetal tissue.

469
00:28:36.384 --> 00:28:38.874
And what we found was that cord blood NK cells

470
00:28:38.954 --> 00:28:42.214
seem

471
00:28:44.214 --> 00:28:47.794
to sit somewhere between developmental and peripheral blood NK cells.

472
00:28:48.334 --> 00:28:51.974
They share cytotoxicity programs very similar to peripheral

473
00:28:52.014 --> 00:28:54.693
blood, but also maintain some of the

474
00:28:55.154 --> 00:28:58.974
developmental features of tissue residency

475
00:28:59.474 --> 00:29:02.334
as well as stemness, similar to fetal NK.

476
00:29:03.024 --> 00:29:06.594
And so perhaps it's through this intermediate state that is at least

477
00:29:06.654 --> 00:29:10.594
partly supporting the encouraging data that we're seeing with

478
00:29:10.634 --> 00:29:14.582
cord blood NK cells.So then we

479
00:29:14.902 --> 00:29:18.522
decided to take our approach to target another antigen called

480
00:29:18.582 --> 00:29:22.562
CD70, which is expressed on many different cancer types, including both

481
00:29:22.602 --> 00:29:24.922
hematologic malignancies and solid tumors.

482
00:29:25.562 --> 00:29:29.142
The preclinical work on the CAR design and optimization and

483
00:29:29.222 --> 00:29:32.792
selection of the optimal co-stimulatory molecule was published in Cancer

484
00:29:32.882 --> 00:29:36.822
Discovery a couple of years ago by Sunil Acharya, and we picked the

485
00:29:36.862 --> 00:29:40.742
best CAR, and we translated that to the clinic, and this was

486
00:29:40.802 --> 00:29:44.702
a CAR that had the extracellular domain of the human CD27

487
00:29:44.742 --> 00:29:47.422
receptor, which is the natural receptor for CD70.

488
00:29:47.842 --> 00:29:51.342
Co-stimulation was through CD28, of course, interleukin-15,

489
00:29:51.842 --> 00:29:55.702
and the safety switch. So from two umbilical cord blood units,

490
00:29:55.782 --> 00:29:59.742
starting from optimal cord blood based on the criteria that I mentioned to

491
00:29:59.822 --> 00:30:03.522
you, we manufactured 250 patient doses at an average

492
00:30:03.862 --> 00:30:07.502
cost of $600. And so we started a dose escalation

493
00:30:07.662 --> 00:30:08.002
study

494
00:30:08.962 --> 00:30:12.702
as a basket study in hematologic malignancies with a

495
00:30:12.762 --> 00:30:15.382
starting cell dose of a flat dose of eight million.

496
00:30:15.772 --> 00:30:19.762
And just to put that into context, usually with autologous CAR T cells,

497
00:30:20.302 --> 00:30:24.142
a dose of 100 to 200 million cells are

498
00:30:24.182 --> 00:30:27.822
infused. So this is a case of a young man that we treated.

499
00:30:27.882 --> 00:30:31.602
It was the eighth relapse of his disease, had received two prior

500
00:30:32.102 --> 00:30:35.542
transplants, and yet he received the eight million NK dose.

501
00:30:35.622 --> 00:30:37.762
You can see he had very extensive disease.

502
00:30:38.182 --> 00:30:42.042
Day 30, day 60 post-infusion, he goes into complete

