522
00:31:47.762 --> 00:31:51.422
six months following infusion, we can still detect these CAR NK

523
00:31:51.542 --> 00:31:53.782
cells in the peripheral blood of the patient.

524
00:31:54.422 --> 00:31:57.962
And this shows the copy

525
00:31:58.042 --> 00:32:01.802
numbers of the CAR transgene in the peripheral blood of the patient, where you can

526
00:32:01.882 --> 00:32:05.662
see really between day three and day 14, there is a massive expansion of

527
00:32:05.702 --> 00:32:09.562
these cells, following by a contraction, as expected of an

528
00:32:09.642 --> 00:32:13.602
antigen-driven response. And then when we tested the activity of

529
00:32:13.642 --> 00:32:16.682
these cells in vitro, you can see that they can kill

530
00:32:16.762 --> 00:32:18.042
CD70-positive

531
00:32:19.002 --> 00:32:21.442
Raji tumor cells very nicely, very similar to the

532
00:32:23.742 --> 00:32:24.682
infusion product.

533
00:32:25.942 --> 00:32:29.542
And then performing single-cell RNA sequencing on the peripheral blood

534
00:32:30.862 --> 00:32:34.362
from this patient, you can really see that the kinetic

535
00:32:34.542 --> 00:32:37.882
of the CAR NK expansion is very

536
00:32:38.002 --> 00:32:41.602
dynamic. And so initially, we see expansion of this

537
00:32:41.782 --> 00:32:45.262
first clone, this clone zero, very early on, and then this

538
00:32:45.322 --> 00:32:49.202
contracts, followed by then emergence of this clone four that

539
00:32:49.212 --> 00:32:53.202
then contributes to the long-term persisting clone.

540
00:32:53.282 --> 00:32:53.632
And

541
00:32:54.942 --> 00:32:58.892
this clone four is transcriptionally

542
00:32:58.982 --> 00:33:02.442
very different to clone zero, suggesting that different

543
00:33:02.522 --> 00:33:06.402
transcriptional programs are dictating the initial response,

544
00:33:06.422 --> 00:33:10.142
the initial proliferation versus the persistence of the cells.

545
00:33:12.562 --> 00:33:16.342
So in this particular CD70 CAR NK trial, the patients were

546
00:33:16.402 --> 00:33:19.691
very heavily pretreated. They'd received a median of eight prior lines of

547
00:33:19.782 --> 00:33:21.842
treatment, and actually,

548
00:33:23.122 --> 00:33:26.882
36% of them had received 10 or more prior lines of

549
00:33:26.922 --> 00:33:28.712
therapy. So very heavily pretreated.

550
00:33:29.142 --> 00:33:32.762
So in view of that and in view of the very excellent safety

551
00:33:33.422 --> 00:33:36.442
data and efficacy and promising

552
00:33:36.502 --> 00:33:40.162
efficacy results, we went to FDA, and we've

553
00:33:40.182 --> 00:33:44.122
received approval for a trial with CD70 CAR NK cells in

554
00:33:44.162 --> 00:33:46.042
patients with lymphoid malignancies

555
00:33:47.242 --> 00:33:49.222
after first or second line of

556
00:33:51.502 --> 00:33:55.092
treatment. And also now we're planning a multicenter study

557
00:33:56.182 --> 00:33:59.762
with our partner hospitals across the United

558
00:33:59.862 --> 00:34:00.222
States.

559
00:34:02.842 --> 00:34:03.582
We've also

560
00:34:04.542 --> 00:34:08.042
taken an approach and taken our CAR NK cells to

561
00:34:08.462 --> 00:34:10.602
treat and target T-cell malignancies.

562
00:34:11.082 --> 00:34:13.002
You heard from Franco

563
00:34:13.862 --> 00:34:17.861
some of the challenges with targeting T-cell

564
00:34:17.922 --> 00:34:21.182
malignancies with CAR T cells in that the antigen is often

565
00:34:21.243 --> 00:34:24.902
shared between healthy T cells and the

566
00:34:24.962 --> 00:34:28.402
tumorous T cells, and as a result of that, that results in

567
00:34:28.422 --> 00:34:31.303
friticide during manufacturing and the risk of

568
00:34:32.402 --> 00:34:35.361
tumor contamination in the infusion product.

569
00:34:35.902 --> 00:34:39.842
So we decided to target a molecule, CD5, that is expressed

570
00:34:39.962 --> 00:34:43.602
on many T-cell malignancies and actually also on some

571
00:34:43.682 --> 00:34:47.022
B-cell malignancies, including mantle cell lymphoma and chronic lymphocytic

572
00:34:47.042 --> 00:34:51.033
leukemia, but absent on NK cells. So again, we did

573
00:34:51.033 --> 00:34:54.862
all the preclinical work in terms of optimizing the CAR design, picking the

574
00:34:54.882 --> 00:34:58.462
right co-stimulatory molecule, et cetera, and then we

575
00:34:59.122 --> 00:35:02.342
picked a design that again included

576
00:35:02.662 --> 00:35:06.622
CD28 co-stimulation, the cytokine IL-15, our

577
00:35:06.682 --> 00:35:10.442
safety switch, and then we took a banked optimal cord

578
00:35:10.482 --> 00:35:13.982
blood unit, expanded the cells, and then we made a

579
00:35:14.022 --> 00:35:17.282
biobank of these. And this is a trial led by my colleague, Dr.

580
00:35:17.842 --> 00:35:21.782
Hosing, dose escalation study. And we decided to put our focus on

581
00:35:21.792 --> 00:35:25.562
a type of leukemia called T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia.

582
00:35:25.622 --> 00:35:26.422
It's a rare

583
00:35:27.542 --> 00:35:29.982
T-cell malignancy, but it has a dismal outcome.

584
00:35:30.002 --> 00:35:33.992
And over the last two decades, really, there hasn't been any improvement

585
00:35:34.002 --> 00:35:36.842
in the outcome of these patients, as you can see from this recent

586
00:35:37.922 --> 00:35:41.882
publication.And so we're still at dose

587
00:35:41.942 --> 00:35:45.742
level one, and I just wanted to share some of these preliminary data with you.

588
00:35:45.822 --> 00:35:47.822
We've treated four patients with TPLAL.

589
00:35:47.862 --> 00:35:51.802
You can see they were all heavily pre-treated, and three of those

590
00:35:51.882 --> 00:35:53.762
patients have gone into complete remission.

591
00:35:54.182 --> 00:35:56.802
And in these flow plots, you can see how

592
00:35:58.042 --> 00:36:01.662
the emergence of our donor CAR NK

593
00:36:01.722 --> 00:36:05.402
cells correlates with disappearance of these TPLAL

594
00:36:05.462 --> 00:36:09.142
cells. Isolating the NK cells from the peripheral blood of the

595
00:36:09.182 --> 00:36:12.822
patients, again, we can see that they are just as good as the infusion

596
00:36:12.922 --> 00:36:14.062
product in clearing

597
00:36:14.882 --> 00:36:18.642
the CD5 positive leukemia cells. So they're

598
00:36:18.682 --> 00:36:20.462
maintaining their functionality.

599
00:36:22.742 --> 00:36:26.702
So then, of course, all of these require CAR engineering,

600
00:36:26.782 --> 00:36:29.942
et cetera. So we asked this question: what if we harness that

601
00:36:29.982 --> 00:36:33.382
CD16 receptor that is important for mediating

602
00:36:33.402 --> 00:36:36.942
antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity and instead

603
00:36:37.002 --> 00:36:40.422
redirect the specificity of NK cells by combining them with

604
00:36:40.462 --> 00:36:42.562
biologic, combining them with antibodies?

605
00:36:43.122 --> 00:36:46.722
So the preclinical work for this approach was led by Lucila

606
00:36:46.782 --> 00:36:48.922
Kerbai, which was a postdoc in my lab.

607
00:36:49.102 --> 00:36:50.762
And now Lucila is a faculty member

608
00:36:51.442 --> 00:36:55.062
in São Paulo, at São Paulo

609
00:36:55.142 --> 00:36:55.822
University

610
00:36:56.862 --> 00:37:00.842
in Brazil. But what she showed is that if we combine

611
00:37:00.882 --> 00:37:04.162
our NK cells with a bispecific NK cell engager called

612
00:37:04.202 --> 00:37:07.942
AFM13, that binds to CD16 on the one

613
00:37:08.022 --> 00:37:11.282
hand and CD30 on the other hand, we can redirect the

614
00:37:11.402 --> 00:37:14.602
specificity of NK cells towards this target.

615
00:37:15.002 --> 00:37:18.922
And I should hasten to add that the AFM13 as a single agent had been

616
00:37:18.942 --> 00:37:22.782
tested in the clinic previously by the company who developed

617
00:37:22.792 --> 00:37:23.022
this

618
00:37:24.102 --> 00:37:24.722
antibody,

619
00:37:25.782 --> 00:37:28.082
and the name of the company was Affimed.

620
00:37:28.502 --> 00:37:32.342
And basically, they had reported a 16% overall response rate

621
00:37:32.382 --> 00:37:36.062
with no complete remissions. So then we took this approach to the

622
00:37:36.122 --> 00:37:39.082
clinic of combining our NK cells with

623
00:37:39.702 --> 00:37:42.782
AFM13. This was work led by Dr. Yago Nieto.

624
00:37:43.482 --> 00:37:47.342
And we published the data recently in 42 patients with Hodgkin lymphoma,

625
00:37:47.482 --> 00:37:50.342
very heavily pre-treated, seven prior lines of therapy.

626
00:37:51.082 --> 00:37:54.322
They'd all had previous CD30 targeting antibodies.

627
00:37:54.382 --> 00:37:57.782
Many of them had had a transplant. They all had progressive disease.

628
00:37:57.842 --> 00:38:00.122
No patient received bridging therapy.

629
00:38:01.042 --> 00:38:04.922
This is an example of before and after, and our response rates were

630
00:38:04.962 --> 00:38:08.942
really pretty astounding in that we saw an overall response rate of

631
00:38:08.982 --> 00:38:12.752
greater than 90% with two-thirds of patients going into complete remission.

632
00:38:15.002 --> 00:38:15.602
However,

633
00:38:16.402 --> 00:38:18.002
in the absence of a

634
00:38:18.942 --> 00:38:22.872
transplant consolidation, many of these patients who'd

635
00:38:22.942 --> 00:38:25.582
achieved a response went on to progress.

636
00:38:26.282 --> 00:38:30.062
And the reason for that was, as one would expect

637
00:38:30.142 --> 00:38:30.862
of the

638
00:38:32.482 --> 00:38:36.472
pharmacokinetic of non-engineered NK cells, these

639
00:38:36.502 --> 00:38:39.942
cells only persisted for a week or two weeks following infusion.

640
00:38:41.762 --> 00:38:45.612
And just because this is of course very different to what we saw with our

641
00:38:45.662 --> 00:38:49.382
CAR design, where the cells were, we observed them to

642
00:38:49.442 --> 00:38:51.062
persist for months, if not

643
00:38:52.262 --> 00:38:54.022
one or two years following infusion.

644
00:38:54.742 --> 00:38:58.062
But I think this study really showed to us the power of

645
00:38:58.522 --> 00:39:02.122
combining biologics with

646
00:39:02.602 --> 00:39:03.482
healthy

647
00:39:04.502 --> 00:39:08.152
NK cells from a good source of

648
00:39:09.002 --> 00:39:12.442
adoptive cell therapy. And this then led us to come up with this

649
00:39:12.542 --> 00:39:13.102
idea

650
00:39:13.902 --> 00:39:15.822
of rather than engineering

651
00:39:16.702 --> 00:39:20.662
a CAR for every specific target, for every specific

652
00:39:20.802 --> 00:39:24.362
disease, what we could actually do is first

653
00:39:24.442 --> 00:39:28.302
endow NK cells with the ability to be combined

654
00:39:28.382 --> 00:39:28.782
with

655
00:39:29.982 --> 00:39:32.762
engagers, with antibodies. So what we did was we

656
00:39:33.682 --> 00:39:36.482
engineered our NK cells to express CD3.

657
00:39:37.302 --> 00:39:40.542
And this allowed then our NK cells to be

658
00:39:41.102 --> 00:39:45.082
combined with T cell engagers. We engineered the

659
00:39:45.142 --> 00:39:49.002
NK cells also to express high-affinity CD16, which then would allow us

660
00:39:49.042 --> 00:39:53.002
to combine them with select monoclonal antibodies

661
00:39:53.042 --> 00:39:53.242
and

662
00:39:54.222 --> 00:39:58.062
also ADCs. We also engineered the NK cells to express

663
00:39:58.101 --> 00:40:01.481
invariant TCR, which then now allows them to

664
00:40:01.541 --> 00:40:04.962
recognize glycolipids presented in the context of

665
00:40:05.362 --> 00:40:06.102
CD1d.

666
00:40:07.582 --> 00:40:11.522
They still express their endogenous receptors, and then they can also

667
00:40:11.562 --> 00:40:15.402
secrete interleukin-15 for persistence.

668
00:40:15.482 --> 00:40:18.382
And in vitro, we demonstrated that these

669
00:40:19.302 --> 00:40:22.402
engineered NK cells that we call Plurilink, when coupled with

670
00:40:22.762 --> 00:40:26.522
EGFR-targeting antibodies, they can eradicate the tumor cells very

671
00:40:26.562 --> 00:40:29.642
nicely. Similarly, with T cell engagers such as

672
00:40:29.742 --> 00:40:32.062
blinatumomab, we saw very nice clearance.

673
00:40:32.562 --> 00:40:36.462
We could also combine them with certain ADCs that

674
00:40:36.602 --> 00:40:40.422
still have an intact IgG, such as brentuximab, and

675
00:40:40.482 --> 00:40:44.382
also with talatuzumab, which targets the DLL3, so

676
00:40:44.402 --> 00:40:48.202
bispecific T cell engager. And actually, in vivo in this mouse model,

677
00:40:48.302 --> 00:40:50.442
you can see that our Plurilink

678
00:40:51.282 --> 00:40:53.962
NK cells with a bispecific T cell engager against

679
00:40:54.222 --> 00:40:57.982
BCMA do actually even better than BCMA CAR NK

680
00:40:58.042 --> 00:41:02.022
cells. So now we've taken this approach to the clinic, and we have

681
00:41:02.082 --> 00:41:03.962
now a clinical trial with these

682
00:41:04.022 --> 00:41:07.862
Plurilink cells combined

683
00:41:07.942 --> 00:41:11.862
with epcor, which is a bispecific T cell engager against

684
00:41:12.342 --> 00:41:15.962
CD20, and tafasitamab which is a

685
00:41:16.042 --> 00:41:19.642
monoclonal antibody targeting CD19 for a dual

686
00:41:19.782 --> 00:41:23.762
targeting approach for lymphoid malignancies led by Dr. Nieto.

687
00:41:24.362 --> 00:41:28.102
And then we also have a second trial of our Plurilink cells plus

688
00:41:28.182 --> 00:41:32.102
tafasitamab targeting CD19 in autoimmune disorders, including

689
00:41:32.222 --> 00:41:35.262
lupus and scleroderma, in collaboration with Dr.

690
00:41:35.482 --> 00:41:39.202
Osasya at UT Health and Dr. Barrera at Baylor

691
00:41:39.262 --> 00:41:41.662
College of Medicine, led by Dr. Hosing at our

692
00:41:41.722 --> 00:41:45.418
center.We are also taking our

693
00:41:45.458 --> 00:41:49.018
approach of adoptive NK cell therapy to targeting

694
00:41:49.498 --> 00:41:53.258
solid tumors. However, here, in addition to engineering the cells

695
00:41:53.338 --> 00:41:56.938
for tumor targeting, we also need to engineer them to

696
00:41:56.998 --> 00:41:58.278
enhance their penetration,

697
00:41:59.158 --> 00:41:59.978
and also to

698
00:42:03.338 --> 00:42:07.248
make them more resistant to the immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment.

699
00:42:08.838 --> 00:42:12.818
CAR T cells have been tested for glioblastoma with local regional

700
00:42:12.838 --> 00:42:16.778
delivery, and interesting, certainly responses

701
00:42:16.858 --> 00:42:20.638
have been observed, but these have been limited by neurotoxicity

702
00:42:21.078 --> 00:42:23.337
and also modest progression-free survival.

703
00:42:23.378 --> 00:42:26.818
So really, there's a need for safer and more effective

704
00:42:28.038 --> 00:42:29.498
therapies in this setting.

705
00:42:31.138 --> 00:42:34.998
So a few years ago, we demonstrated that NK cells are

706
00:42:35.038 --> 00:42:38.338
capable of killing glioblastoma cancer stem cells, but

707
00:42:39.798 --> 00:42:42.958
that TGF-beta is a very important mechanism of

708
00:42:43.018 --> 00:42:46.818
immunosuppression. And then this led us to develop this clinical trial

709
00:42:47.178 --> 00:42:50.818
where using CRISPR gene editing, we deleted the TGF-beta

710
00:42:50.858 --> 00:42:54.738
receptor II gene and also the glucocorticoid receptor gene

711
00:42:54.788 --> 00:42:57.598
to allow the concurrent administration of steroids.

712
00:42:57.638 --> 00:42:59.497
And this is a trial led by my colleague, Dr.

713
00:42:59.558 --> 00:43:03.458
Sharpé Weathers, where patients receive these double knockout cord

714
00:43:03.498 --> 00:43:07.438
blood NK cells intratumorally. There is no cytokine engineering,

715
00:43:07.518 --> 00:43:10.538
so patients receive eight infusions of these, and

716
00:43:11.678 --> 00:43:14.138
with a starting dose of 20 million cells.

717
00:43:15.478 --> 00:43:18.458
We've now treated six patients at dose level one.

718
00:43:19.458 --> 00:43:21.598
All of these patients had refractory disease.

719
00:43:22.038 --> 00:43:25.238
Four out of six patients have achieved stable disease.

720
00:43:25.278 --> 00:43:29.078
This last patient has just received his eighth dose of the

721
00:43:29.138 --> 00:43:32.278
cells, and it's been very well tolerated.

722
00:43:32.798 --> 00:43:35.398
In four patients, we had the opportunity to look at the

723
00:43:37.198 --> 00:43:40.738
tumor before and after giving our NK cells,

724
00:43:41.218 --> 00:43:45.178
and we could demonstrate infiltration

725
00:43:45.238 --> 00:43:45.998
of our

726
00:43:46.858 --> 00:43:50.558
donor NK cells in the tumor tissue, as you can see here, and these

727
00:43:50.678 --> 00:43:54.558
NK cells had an activated transcriptomic

728
00:43:54.638 --> 00:43:58.167
profile. But very interestingly, it appears that our NK cells

729
00:43:58.298 --> 00:43:58.898
also

730
00:44:00.118 --> 00:44:04.058
modulate the myeloid microenvironment in that we

731
00:44:04.098 --> 00:44:07.658
saw a reduction in CD163 positive, IBA

732
00:44:07.758 --> 00:44:11.718
positive macrophage myeloid cells post-infusion,

733
00:44:12.158 --> 00:44:15.438
and a shift from M2 to M1-like

734
00:44:15.838 --> 00:44:19.528
myeloid cells. And these myeloid cells had higher expression

735
00:44:19.638 --> 00:44:19.858
of

736
00:44:21.658 --> 00:44:25.278
OXPHOS-related genes, as well as class one

737
00:44:25.438 --> 00:44:28.258
MHC antigen presentation and activation.

738
00:44:28.928 --> 00:44:31.178
And also very interestingly, we showed that

739
00:44:32.818 --> 00:44:36.798
following NK cells, there was greater infiltration by both

740
00:44:36.898 --> 00:44:39.938
CD8 and CD4 T cells in the tumor

741
00:44:40.018 --> 00:44:43.898
microenvironment, and these have, again, a signature

742
00:44:43.958 --> 00:44:47.478
of antigen receptor signaling and T cell activation.

743
00:44:47.498 --> 00:44:50.558
So really, these NK cells seem to be modulating the immune

744
00:44:50.618 --> 00:44:54.538
microenvironment. So then we ask, can we further enhance

745
00:44:54.578 --> 00:44:58.098
the activity of our NK cells against glioblastoma by

746
00:44:58.178 --> 00:45:02.058
cytokine engineering? And this is work that was led by Myra Shanley in the group,

747
00:45:02.518 --> 00:45:05.858
where she demonstrated that if we engineer NK cells with

748
00:45:05.958 --> 00:45:09.838
interleukin-21, this can really enhance the activity of

749
00:45:09.898 --> 00:45:13.738
our NK cells against glioblastoma, and this was published last

750
00:45:13.778 --> 00:45:17.478
year. But Myra showed that IL-21 is superior to

751
00:45:17.518 --> 00:45:21.448
IL-15 and results in better mitochondrial function as well as

752
00:45:21.478 --> 00:45:23.478
polyfunctionality of these cells.

753
00:45:23.498 --> 00:45:26.998
And this was mediated through induction of CBPD, and you can see

754
00:45:27.038 --> 00:45:30.898
here one injection of these IL-21 NK cells to these mice

755
00:45:30.998 --> 00:45:33.098
can cure them, whereas IL-15 can't.

756
00:45:33.558 --> 00:45:37.298
So based on that, now we've developed a next generation CAR design

757
00:45:38.318 --> 00:45:42.258
where the vector, there's a dual targeting of IL-13 receptor,

758
00:45:42.878 --> 00:45:46.718
alpha and EGFR V3, together with IL-21 armoring

759
00:45:47.078 --> 00:45:50.798
and the safety switch. And in addition, we've also incorporated double

760
00:45:50.838 --> 00:45:54.618
knockout targeting TGF-beta receptor II and the NR3C1

761
00:45:54.718 --> 00:45:54.958
gene.

762
00:45:55.958 --> 00:45:59.838
And you can see here, again, one injection can cure the animals in an orthotopic

763
00:45:59.938 --> 00:46:03.078
model. And so now we've taken this to the clinic.

764
00:46:03.098 --> 00:46:06.758
In the interest of time, I'm going to skip all the IND-enabling

765
00:46:06.798 --> 00:46:10.538
studies that we had to do. But just to show that from one

766
00:46:11.218 --> 00:46:14.798
cord blood unit, we've manufactured 70 patient doses with an

767
00:46:14.858 --> 00:46:18.058
excellent CAR transduction efficiency and dual knockout efficiency.

768
00:46:18.138 --> 00:46:21.978
This was work done by Mariam Imari in our group, and with an average cost of

769
00:46:22.058 --> 00:46:23.518
only a couple of thousand dollars.

770
00:46:24.078 --> 00:46:27.738
And so we've just received approval from FDA to move forward with a

771
00:46:27.778 --> 00:46:31.268
clinical trial that will be led by Dr. Ene together with Dr.

772
00:46:31.538 --> 00:46:33.038
Lang in our

773
00:46:34.518 --> 00:46:38.018
neurosurgical department. And here we will be

774
00:46:38.438 --> 00:46:39.938
testing the best route of delivery.

775
00:46:40.038 --> 00:46:43.348
Patients will be randomized to receiving either intratumoral,

776
00:46:43.558 --> 00:46:47.068
intraventricular, or intra-arterial injections of the cells.

777
00:46:47.378 --> 00:46:49.998
So we'll test both safety and efficacy.

778
00:46:50.008 --> 00:46:52.098
And finally, we also have a very

779
00:46:53.318 --> 00:46:56.188
expansive discovery platform that was established by Dr.

780
00:46:56.438 --> 00:47:00.258
Bidesh Das in the group, and where we perform

781
00:47:00.338 --> 00:47:04.208
genome-wide CRISPR screen on primary human NK cells and CAR

782
00:47:04.258 --> 00:47:06.678
NK cells, where they're being exposed to

783
00:47:08.138 --> 00:47:11.858
